<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WOMEN’S LEAGUE OF BURMA     (WLB)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">WOMEN’S LEAGUE OF BURMA  (WLB)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Women’s League of Burma (WLB) is an umbrella organisation comprising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> thirteen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">women’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NGOs from different ethnic areas in Burma, embodying the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> federal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> spirit of the 1947 Panglong Agreement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">WLB was founded on 9th December, 1999 with the mission to work for women’s empowerment and the increased participation of women in all spheres of society, particularly peace and national reconciliation processes through capacity building, advocacy, research and documentation. Our constitution mand</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ates each member organisation</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> send representatives to serve in a variety of positions throughout the Congress, Presidium Board, Secretariat, and Pr</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ogram Coordinators. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The activities and expertise of each memb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er organisation is brought into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collaborative review through the Presidium board and form the basis of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> nationwide advocacy strategies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With multi-ethnic leadership and staffing</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we ensure our vision is balanced by viewpoints from across Burma.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.Burmese Women’s Union (BWU)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.Karen Women’s Organisation (KWO)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.Kachin Women’s Association (KWAT)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.Karrenni National Women’s Organisation (KNWO) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.Kayan Women’s Organisation (KYWO) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.Kuki Women’s Human Rights Organisation (KWHRO)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.Lahu Women’s Organisation (LWO)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.Palaung Women’s Organisation (PWO)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9.Pa-O Women’s Union (PWU)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10.Rakhaing Women’s Union (RWU)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11.Shan Women’s Action Network (SWAN)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12.Tavoy Women’s Union (TWU)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13.Women’s Rights and Welfare Association of Burma (WRWAB)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">EXECUTIVE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. Given the rapidly changing environment in Burma, how should DfID’s programme develop?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">SUPPORT ETHNIC DIVERSITY - PARTICIPATORY METHODS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: Engaging with diverse Burmese civil society and communities is crucial to ensure DfID’s program develops in most effective and sustainable manner. The programme risks reinforcing the uneven development that fuels many of Burma’s conflicts if it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">channels its funds through larger organisations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based in capital cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Bolstering the government at the expense of ethnic groups risks repeating the past.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">EMPOWER WOMEN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: DfID’s Operational Report 2011-2015 highlights a ‘strong’ focus on women and girls. Yet the programs plans extend to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">targeted interventions to reduce maternal mortality and increase women’s access to credit”. A strong focus on women and girls must extend this gendered perspective to governance, security and humanitarian assistance.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. DFID provision of funding and advice to civil society organizations in Burma, particularly for strengthening coalitions, advocacy, research and monitoring capabilities. How successful has this been?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ENGAGE WITH ESTABLISHED CIVIL SOCIETY:</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2010 saw incremental increases in civil liberties; relief work and political activism in Burma has been operating long before it’s ‘opening’</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These networks can advise DfID, </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">di</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recting officials to established relief networks </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with no requirement for consultation fees.</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Unlike current reliance on costly external consultants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">CROSS-BORDER</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> AID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Reluctance to engage with cross-border aid means DfID sidelines established civil society netw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orks that stretch across Burma. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is based on a false assessment that NGOs headquartered in the borders carry out activities there. With headquarters outside of Burma organisations were able to access transnational funding and advocacy in a manner impossible from inside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will take the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">example of relief work and empowerment programs in Kachin state (which only saw aid blockades lifted in June this year) to demonstrate th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e importance of supporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">established initiatives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. What role should DFID play in helping to resolve ethnic tensions?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">GO BEYOND CEASEFIRES:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The international community sees ceasefires as the signal of peace, as an expert development institution DfID must go further. Land grabs, predatory investment and exclusion of civil society is set to reproduce the economic and political marginalisation that fuels ongoing conflicts.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. How effectively is DFID working with the FCO and other UK Government Departments, and how might this improve?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">END IMPUNITY FOR SEXUAL VIOLENECE:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Despite the FCO’s focus on ending impunity for sexual violence; DfID’s plans for Burma do not mention this. The coordinated efforts of the FCO, DfID and other UK government departments will be crucial in ensuring abuses are brought to international attention and that Burmese victims access justice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">COMMISSION OF INQUIRY:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Burmese organisations have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">documenting the high incidence of rape throughout Burma’s conflicts and decades of militar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y rule but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lack of international verification means this evidence is sidelined.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Given the rapidly changing environment in Burma, how should DfID’s programme develop?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">DIVERSIFY FOCUS GROUPS:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Incremental improvements in civil and political rights must not distract from continuing systematic human rights abuses and extreme inequalities in social and economic rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, particularly in rural and ethnic areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Changes are largely confined to urban areas and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the media sphere.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> DfID’s dependence on NGOs based in populous urban centres risks contributing to the uneven development process, strengthening already powerful elites at the expense of those who most need their support. Burma is a complex nation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">diverse ethnic communities; yet politics continues to be elite Burman driven. DfID must not exacerbate the centralisation of resources by over-focussing on Rangoon or Naypyidaw.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">GENDER: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID’s Operational Report 2011-2015 highlights a ‘strong’ focus on women and girls. Yet the programs plans extend to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">targeted interventions to reduce maternal mortality and increase women’s access to credit”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite ratifying CEDAW in 1997 Burmese women and girls suffer extensive discrimination, sexual violence, human trafficking and have little to no access to human rights protection or justice.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Burma’s refusal to sign the recent United Nations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="color:#0b0b0b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Declaration of Commitment to end Sexual Violence in Conflict’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a case in point</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While women have suffered the worst effects of Burma’s ongoing conflicts they continue to be sidelined from the peace process. Negotiations have not included female representatives at any stage. The government set up Myanmar Peace Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (MPC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is all male and there are few women involved in its negotiating partner, the United Nationalities Federation Council (UNFC). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This month the USDP encouragingly announced a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National Strategic Plan for the Advancement of Women (NSPAW)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> however this requires close mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nitoring by bodies such as DfID as the National Women’s machinery continues to be run by government organised NGOs (GONGOs).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Political empowerment must be a key focus of DfID’s plan to include the other ‘half of the population’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This cannot be achieved without support to existing women’s organisat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ions that have been sidelined f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m development funding; how can we expect political empowerment without supporting the very organisations, educational programs and advocacy networks that can enable this?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Legal changes are essential, the 2008 constitution enshrines impunity for war crimes and bars women from political access; in the meantime </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aid must support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programs for young female leaders, educational access for women and girls, redress for sexual violence and domestic abuse and promoting women’s access to dec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ision-making positions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:150pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pillar / Strategic Priority</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:292.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Governance &amp; Security </span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:150pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Indicator:  </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:292.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Number of people supported to have choice and control over their own development, through DFID support.</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:150pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Baseline:  </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:292.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nil at 2010 (Output indicator)                                              </span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:4.5pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:150pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Expected Result:   </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:292.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">94,000 people by 2015</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (inc. 76,000 women).</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> DFID provision of funding and advice to civil society organizations in Burma, particularly for strengthening coalitions, advocacy, research and monitoring capabilities. How successful has this been?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4) ESTABLISHED NGOS SIDELINED</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Burma does not suffer a dearth of civil society organisations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A tendency to centralise funding in Yangon and to look to newer organisations means DfID may fail to reach civil society networks that support those most in need. Since 2010 manifold new NGOs have be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en established particularly in R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on, while encouraging, these green organizations do not have the technical expertise or the geographical reach that established NGOs provide. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">5) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">CONFLICT ZONES:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Communities in conflict areas and ‘ethnic states’ have the highest mortality rates and suffer the most extreme levels of poverty; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a prime example is Kachin state where restrictions on aid were lifted only in June this year (2013). Yet, local relief programs have long been working in Kachin areas:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KWAT (Kachin Women’s Association) funds and organises diverse projects across Kachin state: such as their health programs in </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mai Ja Yang, in the south of Kachin State. The activities include adolesce</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt reproductive health training</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, school hea</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lth care and awareness training</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a malaria and tuberculosis prevent</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion and medication program, out</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reach health campaigns to local villages, and a daily mother and childcare clinic in Ja Reng Yang. </span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">They organise extensive </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">political empowerment projects in Myitkyina comprising a political forum and democracy and human rights training for young Kachin students (mainly women) and outreach programs to local communities on the political process and how to vote at the time of elections. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">CROSS-BORDER AID:</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Df</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ID has continued to be reluctant to engage with organisations headquartered in the border areas, despite being the predominate location of conflict and hence the gravest human rights abuses, developmental needs and displaced persons. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Df</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ID maintains that it has a comparative advantage working with groups inside Burma, even that this brings them closer to the grassroots. This is based on a false assessment that NGOs headquartered in the borders carry out activities there; over 90% of the work of organisations such as KWAT is carried out inside Burma. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">EXILE MYTH</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sidelining cross-border NGOs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">implies that people fleeing forced conscription, counter-insurgency, victims of rape, people whose villages were inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inerated or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> families killed are somehow out of touch with Burma’s internal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">situation. These people are acutely aware of what it means to live under the constant threat of war; from their position of comparative safety NGOs set up in exile have been providing vital support for their communities inside for decades. With headquarters outside of Burma organisations were able to access transnational funding and advocacy in a manner impossible from inside. They continue to document human rights violations and crimes against humanity that groups inside, forced to tread carefully around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘ceasefires’ or ‘peace’ are unable to speak out on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> look to umbrella or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ganizations that bring together</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> smaller grassroots NGOs. </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unlike relying on costly external consultants to map out poten</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tial partners or areas of need,</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> existin</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g networks</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can direct DfID officials to areas of need and relevant NGOs with no requirement for consultation fees.</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to years of experience such organisations can engage on the kind of consultation level and with the international standards that large funding bodies require</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  For example; m</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ost recently WLB</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in partnership with WON (Women’s Organisational Network of Myanmar)</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has brought </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">AJAR (Asia Justice and Rights)</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into contact with several of its member organisations to work towards a Survivors of Sexual Violence Network and training program for researchers on sexual </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">violence. This is what the WLB and similar organisations exist</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to do; bring together diverse civil society organisation</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s working for change in Burma.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">. What role should DfID play in helping to resolve ethnic tensions?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">UNEVEN DEVELOPMENT/CEASEFIRES:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Situation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The focus on ceasefires with ethnic armed forces as a “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant positive development”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risks overlooking the lack of actual improvement for communities living in ceasefire areas. There are no official monitoring mechanisms for ceasefire accords.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ivil society organisations have produced numerous reports outlining how militarized development extends under the cover of ceasefires. In Karen areas: no soldiers have left, land-confiscation and displacement is rife and selective business deals with former ethnic army leaders encourages a corrupt system marginalising the wider community</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID must ensure that ceasefire agreements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do not provide a cloak for destructive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> industrialisation that will produce anew the economic and political marginalisation that lies at the root of many ethnic insurgencies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rograms for ‘capacity building’ have multiplied; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">however land confiscation, rapid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">construction of dams and power plants ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> return to areas with little agricultural promise. While the international community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasises ceasefires as the signal of peace, DfID must ensure that this ‘peace’ means sustainable and equitable development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not merely the silence of guns.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">HUMANITARIAN AID:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID should continue to prioritise desperately needed support for Muslim communities displaced by ongoing violence in 2013. This crucial humanitarian assistance must also extend to other ethnic communities similarly displaced by violence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and facing denial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of citizenship rights. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the upcoming Census, DfID’s involvement in mapping out different ethnic communities by accessing local networks excluded from government overviews is essential.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> How effectively is DFID working with the FCO and other UK Government Departments, and how might this improve?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12) IMPUNITY FOR SEXUAL VIOLENCE: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The FCO’s ‘Preventing Sexual Violence Initiative’ needs to be enforced in Burma. DfID and the FCO must work closely together on this. While Hague’s statement that the UK is committed to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shattering the culture of impunity that surrounds sexual violence in conflict”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; Burma’s current 2008 constitution includes provisions for Burmese military amnesty. Article 445 states </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No proceeding shall be instituted against the said Councils or any members thereof or any member of the Government, in respect of any act done in the execution of their respective duties.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This enshrined impunity is compounded by Burma’s refusal to sign up to the UN ‘</span><span style="color:#0b0b0b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Declaration of Commitment to end Sexual Violence in Conflict’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13) COMMISSION OF INQUIRY:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID and the FCO must work together with the UK Government in pushing for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Commission of Inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into human rights violations, particularly sexual violence. While Burmese women’s organisations and human rights organisations have been documenting the high incidence of rape throughout Burma’s conflicts and decades of military rule a lack of international verification means this evidence is sidelined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The coordinated efforts of the FCO, DfID and other UK government departments will be crucial in ensuring these abuses are brought to international attention and that Burmese victims access justice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CEDAW Shadow Report 2008 http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cedaw/docs/ngos/Women_Burma42.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Adapted from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfID Burma Operational Plan 2011-2015. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘Headline Results Table’ pg 5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfID Burma Operational Plan 2011-2015. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Figure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">8) Human Rights Assessment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">See KHRG (Karen Human Rights Group) continually updated reports on cease-fires across the region: </span><a href="http://www.khrg.org/reports/issue/ceasefire"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.khrg.org/reports/issue/ceasefire</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Caught in a Two-Front War in Post-Ceasefire Karen State’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Saw </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Greh Moo. Salween Institute. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.salweeninstitute.org/home---two-front-war.html</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Speech</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Enhancing Accountability for Sexual Violence in Conflict’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/foreign-commonwealth-office"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Delivered on:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">26 September 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Rt Hon William Hague MP at United Nations</span></p></body></html>